\int x\sqrt{x^2 - 4}\,dx
\int x\sqrt{x^2 - 4}\,dx
\quad u = x^2 - 4 \implies du = 2x\,dx \iff \dfrac 12\,du = x\,dx.
\frac 12 \int  u^{1/2}\,du
\begin{align}\int x\sqrt{x^2 - 4} \,dx & =  \int (\underbrace{x^2 - 4}_{u})^{1/2}\,\underbrace{x\,dx}_{\frac 12 \,du}\\ \\  & = \frac  12  \int  u^{1/2}\,du \\ \\ & =\frac 12 \dfrac {u^{3/2}}{3/2} +C \\ \\ & = \frac 13 u^{3/2} + C\end{align}
\,u = x^2 - 4\,
\frac 13(x^2 - 4)^{3/2} + C
\int x\sqrt{x^2-4}\,dx=\frac12\int(x^2-4)'\sqrt{x^2-4}\,dx=\frac12\frac23(x^2-4)^{3/2}+C=\ldots
